\title{Pymc Bayesian Modeling}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Bayesian modeling with PyMC. Build hierarchical models, MCMC (NUTS), variational inference, LOO/WAIC comparison, posterior checks, for probabilistic programming and inference."}

\subtree{
\title{PyMC Bayesian Modeling}
\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{PyMC is a Python library for Bayesian modeling and probabilistic programming. Build, fit, validate, and compare Bayesian models using PyMC's modern API (version 5.x+), including hierarchical models, MCMC sampling (NUTS), variational inference, and model comparison (LOO, WAIC).}
}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{This skill should be used when:}

\ul{
\li{Building Bayesian models (linear/logistic regression, hierarchical models, time series, etc.)}
\li{Performing MCMC sampling or variational inference}
\li{Conducting prior/posterior predictive checks}
\li{Diagnosing sampling issues (divergences, convergence, ESS)}
\li{Comparing multiple models using information criteria (LOO, WAIC)}
\li{Implementing uncertainty quantification through Bayesian methods}
\li{Working with hierarchical/multilevel data structures}
\li{Handling missing data or measurement error in a principled way}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Standard Bayesian Workflow}
\p{Follow this workflow for building and validating Bayesian models:}

\subtree{
\title{1. Data Preparation}
\pre{\startverb
import pymc as pm
import arviz as az
import numpy as np

# Load and prepare data
X = ...  # Predictors
y = ...  # Outcomes

# Standardize predictors for better sampling
X_mean = X.mean(axis=0)
X_std = X.std(axis=0)
X_scaled = (X - X_mean) / X_std
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Key practices:}}

\ul{
\li{Standardize continuous predictors (improves sampling efficiency)}
\li{Center outcomes when possible}
\li{Handle missing data explicitly (treat as parameters)}
\li{Use named dimensions with \code{\startverb coords\stopverb} for clarity}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Model Building}
\pre{\startverb
coords = {
    'predictors': ['var1', 'var2', 'var3'],
    'obs_id': np.arange(len(y))
}

with pm.Model(coords=coords) as model:
    # Priors
    alpha = pm.Normal('alpha', mu=0, sigma=1)
    beta = pm.Normal('beta', mu=0, sigma=1, dims='predictors')
    sigma = pm.HalfNormal('sigma', sigma=1)

    # Linear predictor
    mu = alpha + pm.math.dot(X_scaled, beta)

    # Likelihood
    y_obs = pm.Normal('y_obs', mu=mu, sigma=sigma, observed=y, dims='obs_id')
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Key practices:}}

\ul{
\li{Use weakly informative priors (not flat priors)}
\li{Use \code{\startverb HalfNormal\stopverb} or \code{\startverb Exponential\stopverb} for scale parameters}
\li{Use named dimensions (\code{\startverb dims\stopverb}) instead of \code{\startverb shape\stopverb} when possible}
\li{Use \code{\startverb pm.Data()\stopverb} for values that will be updated for predictions}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Prior Predictive Check}
\p{\strong{Always validate priors before fitting:}}

\pre{\startverb
with model:
    prior_pred = pm.sample_prior_predictive(samples=1000, random_seed=42)

# Visualize
az.plot_ppc(prior_pred, group='prior')
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Check:}}

\ul{
\li{Do prior predictions span reasonable values?}
\li{Are extreme values plausible given domain knowledge?}
\li{If priors generate implausible data, adjust and re-check}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Fit Model}
\pre{\startverb
with model:
    # Optional: Quick exploration with ADVI
    # approx = pm.fit(n=20000)

    # Full MCMC inference
    idata = pm.sample(
        draws=2000,
        tune=1000,
        chains=4,
        target_accept=0.9,
        random_seed=42,
        idata_kwargs={'log_likelihood': True}  # For model comparison
    )
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Key parameters:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb draws=2000\stopverb}: Number of samples per chain}
\li{\code{\startverb tune=1000\stopverb}: Warmup samples (discarded)}
\li{\code{\startverb chains=4\stopverb}: Run 4 chains for convergence checking}
\li{\code{\startverb target_accept=0.9\stopverb}: Higher for difficult posteriors (0.95-0.99)}
\li{Include \code{\startverb log_likelihood=True\stopverb} for model comparison}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. Check Diagnostics}
\p{\strong{Use the diagnostic script:}}

\pre{\startverb
from scripts.model_diagnostics import check_diagnostics

results = check_diagnostics(idata, var_names=['alpha', 'beta', 'sigma'])
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Check:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{R-hat < 1.01}: Chains have converged}
\li{\strong{ESS > 400}: Sufficient effective samples}
\li{\strong{No divergences}: NUTS sampled successfully}
\li{\strong{Trace plots}: Chains should mix well (fuzzy caterpillar)}
}

\p{\strong{If issues arise:}}

\ul{
\li{Divergences → Increase \code{\startverb target_accept=0.95\stopverb}, use non-centered parameterization}
\li{Low ESS → Sample more draws, reparameterize to reduce correlation}
\li{High R-hat → Run longer, check for multimodality}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{6. Posterior Predictive Check}
\p{\strong{Validate model fit:}}

\pre{\startverb
with model:
    pm.sample_posterior_predictive(idata, extend_inferencedata=True, random_seed=42)

# Visualize
az.plot_ppc(idata)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Check:}}

\ul{
\li{Do posterior predictions capture observed data patterns?}
\li{Are systematic deviations evident (model misspecification)?}
\li{Consider alternative models if fit is poor}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{7. Analyze Results}
\pre{\startverb
# Summary statistics
print(az.summary(idata, var_names=['alpha', 'beta', 'sigma']))

# Posterior distributions
az.plot_posterior(idata, var_names=['alpha', 'beta', 'sigma'])

# Coefficient estimates
az.plot_forest(idata, var_names=['beta'], combined=True)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{8. Make Predictions}
\pre{\startverb
X_new = ...  # New predictor values
X_new_scaled = (X_new - X_mean) / X_std

with model:
    pm.set_data({'X_scaled': X_new_scaled})
    post_pred = pm.sample_posterior_predictive(
        idata.posterior,
        var_names=['y_obs'],
        random_seed=42
    )

# Extract prediction intervals
y_pred_mean = post_pred.posterior_predictive['y_obs'].mean(dim=['chain', 'draw'])
y_pred_hdi = az.hdi(post_pred.posterior_predictive, var_names=['y_obs'])
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Model Patterns}
\subtree{
\title{Linear Regression}
\p{For continuous outcomes with linear relationships:}

\pre{\startverb
with pm.Model() as linear_model:
    alpha = pm.Normal('alpha', mu=0, sigma=10)
    beta = pm.Normal('beta', mu=0, sigma=10, shape=n_predictors)
    sigma = pm.HalfNormal('sigma', sigma=1)

    mu = alpha + pm.math.dot(X, beta)
    y = pm.Normal('y', mu=mu, sigma=sigma, observed=y_obs)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Use template:} \code{\startverb assets/linear_regression_template.py\stopverb}}
}

\subtree{
\title{Logistic Regression}
\p{For binary outcomes:}

\pre{\startverb
with pm.Model() as logistic_model:
    alpha = pm.Normal('alpha', mu=0, sigma=10)
    beta = pm.Normal('beta', mu=0, sigma=10, shape=n_predictors)

    logit_p = alpha + pm.math.dot(X, beta)
    y = pm.Bernoulli('y', logit_p=logit_p, observed=y_obs)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Hierarchical Models}
\p{For grouped data (use non-centered parameterization):}

\pre{\startverb
with pm.Model(coords={'groups': group_names}) as hierarchical_model:
    # Hyperpriors
    mu_alpha = pm.Normal('mu_alpha', mu=0, sigma=10)
    sigma_alpha = pm.HalfNormal('sigma_alpha', sigma=1)

    # Group-level (non-centered)
    alpha_offset = pm.Normal('alpha_offset', mu=0, sigma=1, dims='groups')
    alpha = pm.Deterministic('alpha', mu_alpha + sigma_alpha * alpha_offset, dims='groups')

    # Observation-level
    mu = alpha[group_idx]
    sigma = pm.HalfNormal('sigma', sigma=1)
    y = pm.Normal('y', mu=mu, sigma=sigma, observed=y_obs)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Use template:} \code{\startverb assets/hierarchical_model_template.py\stopverb}}

\p{\strong{Critical:} Always use non-centered parameterization for hierarchical models to avoid divergences.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Poisson Regression}
\p{For count data:}

\pre{\startverb
with pm.Model() as poisson_model:
    alpha = pm.Normal('alpha', mu=0, sigma=10)
    beta = pm.Normal('beta', mu=0, sigma=10, shape=n_predictors)

    log_lambda = alpha + pm.math.dot(X, beta)
    y = pm.Poisson('y', mu=pm.math.exp(log_lambda), observed=y_obs)
\stopverb}

\p{For overdispersed counts, use \code{\startverb NegativeBinomial\stopverb} instead.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Time Series}
\p{For autoregressive processes:}

\pre{\startverb
with pm.Model() as ar_model:
    sigma = pm.HalfNormal('sigma', sigma=1)
    rho = pm.Normal('rho', mu=0, sigma=0.5, shape=ar_order)
    init_dist = pm.Normal.dist(mu=0, sigma=sigma)

    y = pm.AR('y', rho=rho, sigma=sigma, init_dist=init_dist, observed=y_obs)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Model Comparison}
\subtree{
\title{Comparing Models}
\p{Use LOO or WAIC for model comparison:}

\pre{\startverb
from scripts.model_comparison import compare_models, check_loo_reliability

# Fit models with log_likelihood
models = {
    'Model1': idata1,
    'Model2': idata2,
    'Model3': idata3
}

# Compare using LOO
comparison = compare_models(models, ic='loo')

# Check reliability
check_loo_reliability(models)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Interpretation:}}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Δloo < 2}: Models are similar, choose simpler model}
\li{\strong{2 < Δloo < 4}: Weak evidence for better model}
\li{\strong{4 < Δloo < 10}: Moderate evidence}
\li{\strong{Δloo > 10}: Strong evidence for better model}
}

\p{\strong{Check Pareto-k values:}}

\ul{
\li{k < 0.7: LOO reliable}
\li{k > 0.7: Consider WAIC or k-fold CV}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Model Averaging}
\p{When models are similar, average predictions:}

\pre{\startverb
from scripts.model_comparison import model_averaging

averaged_pred, weights = model_averaging(models, var_name='y_obs')
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Distribution Selection Guide}
\subtree{
\title{For Priors}
\p{\strong{Scale parameters} (σ, τ):}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb pm.HalfNormal('sigma', sigma=1)\stopverb} - Default choice}
\li{\code{\startverb pm.Exponential('sigma', lam=1)\stopverb} - Alternative}
\li{\code{\startverb pm.Gamma('sigma', alpha=2, beta=1)\stopverb} - More informative}
}

\p{\strong{Unbounded parameters}:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb pm.Normal('theta', mu=0, sigma=1)\stopverb} - For standardized data}
\li{\code{\startverb pm.StudentT('theta', nu=3, mu=0, sigma=1)\stopverb} - Robust to outliers}
}

\p{\strong{Positive parameters}:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb pm.LogNormal('theta', mu=0, sigma=1)\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb pm.Gamma('theta', alpha=2, beta=1)\stopverb}}
}

\p{\strong{Probabilities}:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb pm.Beta('p', alpha=2, beta=2)\stopverb} - Weakly informative}
\li{\code{\startverb pm.Uniform('p', lower=0, upper=1)\stopverb} - Non-informative (use sparingly)}
}

\p{\strong{Correlation matrices}:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb pm.LKJCorr('corr', n=n_vars, eta=2)\stopverb} - eta=1 uniform, eta>1 prefers identity}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{For Likelihoods}
\p{\strong{Continuous outcomes}:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb pm.Normal('y', mu=mu, sigma=sigma)\stopverb} - Default for continuous data}
\li{\code{\startverb pm.StudentT('y', nu=nu, mu=mu, sigma=sigma)\stopverb} - Robust to outliers}
}

\p{\strong{Count data}:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb pm.Poisson('y', mu=lambda)\stopverb} - Equidispersed counts}
\li{\code{\startverb pm.NegativeBinomial('y', mu=mu, alpha=alpha)\stopverb} - Overdispersed counts}
\li{\code{\startverb pm.ZeroInflatedPoisson('y', psi=psi, mu=mu)\stopverb} - Excess zeros}
}

\p{\strong{Binary outcomes}:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb pm.Bernoulli('y', p=p)\stopverb} or \code{\startverb pm.Bernoulli('y', logit_p=logit_p)\stopverb}}
}

\p{\strong{Categorical outcomes}:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb pm.Categorical('y', p=probs)\stopverb}}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/distributions.md\stopverb} for comprehensive distribution reference}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Sampling and Inference}
\subtree{
\title{MCMC with NUTS}
\p{Default and recommended for most models:}

\pre{\startverb
idata = pm.sample(
    draws=2000,
    tune=1000,
    chains=4,
    target_accept=0.9,
    random_seed=42
)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Adjust when needed:}}

\ul{
\li{Divergences → \code{\startverb target_accept=0.95\stopverb} or higher}
\li{Slow sampling → Use ADVI for initialization}
\li{Discrete parameters → Use \code{\startverb pm.Metropolis()\stopverb} for discrete vars}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Variational Inference}
\p{Fast approximation for exploration or initialization:}

\pre{\startverb
with model:
    approx = pm.fit(n=20000, method='advi')

    # Use for initialization
    start = approx.sample(return_inferencedata=False)[0]
    idata = pm.sample(start=start)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Trade-offs:}}

\ul{
\li{Much faster than MCMC}
\li{Approximate (may underestimate uncertainty)}
\li{Good for large models or quick exploration}
}

\p{\strong{See:} \code{\startverb references/sampling_inference.md\stopverb} for detailed sampling guide}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Diagnostic Scripts}
\subtree{
\title{Comprehensive Diagnostics}
\pre{\startverb
from scripts.model_diagnostics import create_diagnostic_report

create_diagnostic_report(
    idata,
    var_names=['alpha', 'beta', 'sigma'],
    output_dir='diagnostics/'
)
\stopverb}

\p{Creates:}

\ul{
\li{Trace plots}
\li{Rank plots (mixing check)}
\li{Autocorrelation plots}
\li{Energy plots}
\li{ESS evolution}
\li{Summary statistics CSV}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Diagnostic Check}
\pre{\startverb
from scripts.model_diagnostics import check_diagnostics

results = check_diagnostics(idata)
\stopverb}

\p{Checks R-hat, ESS, divergences, and tree depth.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Issues and Solutions}
\subtree{
\title{Divergences}
\p{\strong{Symptom:} \code{\startverb idata.sample_stats.diverging.sum() > 0\stopverb}}

\p{\strong{Solutions:}}

\ol{
\li{Increase \code{\startverb target_accept=0.95\stopverb} or \code{\startverb 0.99\stopverb}}
\li{Use non-centered parameterization (hierarchical models)}
\li{Add stronger priors to constrain parameters}
\li{Check for model misspecification}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Low Effective Sample Size}
\p{\strong{Symptom:} \code{\startverb ESS < 400\stopverb}}

\p{\strong{Solutions:}}

\ol{
\li{Sample more draws: \code{\startverb draws=5000\stopverb}}
\li{Reparameterize to reduce posterior correlation}
\li{Use QR decomposition for regression with correlated predictors}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{High R-hat}
\p{\strong{Symptom:} \code{\startverb R-hat > 1.01\stopverb}}

\p{\strong{Solutions:}}

\ol{
\li{Run longer chains: \code{\startverb tune=2000, draws=5000\stopverb}}
\li{Check for multimodality}
\li{Improve initialization with ADVI}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Slow Sampling}
\p{\strong{Solutions:}}

\ol{
\li{Use ADVI initialization}
\li{Reduce model complexity}
\li{Increase parallelization: \code{\startverb cores=8, chains=8\stopverb}}
\li{Use variational inference if appropriate}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Best Practices}
\subtree{
\title{Model Building}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Always standardize predictors} for better sampling}
\li{\strong{Use weakly informative priors} (not flat)}
\li{\strong{Use named dimensions} (\code{\startverb dims\stopverb}) for clarity}
\li{\strong{Non-centered parameterization} for hierarchical models}
\li{\strong{Check prior predictive} before fitting}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Sampling}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Run multiple chains} (at least 4) for convergence}
\li{\strong{Use \code{\startverb target_accept=0.9\stopverb}} as baseline (higher if needed)}
\li{\strong{Include \code{\startverb log_likelihood=True\stopverb}} for model comparison}
\li{\strong{Set random seed} for reproducibility}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Validation}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Check diagnostics} before interpretation (R-hat, ESS, divergences)}
\li{\strong{Posterior predictive check} for model validation}
\li{\strong{Compare multiple models} when appropriate}
\li{\strong{Report uncertainty} (HDI intervals, not just point estimates)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\ol{
\li{Start simple, add complexity gradually}
\li{Prior predictive check → Fit → Diagnostics → Posterior predictive check}
\li{Iterate on model specification based on checks}
\li{Document assumptions and prior choices}
}
}
}

